<div class="entry-content primary-content-column columns small-12 medium-8">
<p>Last month, Donald Trump <a href="https://twitter.com/realdonaldtrump/status/1236778368533700609?lang=en" rel="noopener noreferrer">retweeted</a> a doctored photo of himself playing the fiddle that was labeled &ldquo;My next piece is called: nothing can stop what&rsquo;s coming.&rdquo; It was clearly an homage to the Emperor Nero who so infamously made music while Rome burned. To it, the president added this comment: &ldquo;Who knows what this means, but it sounds good to me!&rdquo;</p>
<p>Whether Trump is fiddling these days or not, one thing is certain: in a Nero-like fashion, he continues to be irresponsibly unresponsive to the crisis caused by Covid-19. One reason may be that, however inadvertently, the arrival of the pandemic has helped green-light plans and projects he&rsquo;s held dear to his heart and that had, before the crisis, repeatedly encountered opposition.</p>
<p>Here are six examples of how the coronavirus, like a malign magic wand, has helped cast a disempowering spell over that opposition and so furthered Trump&rsquo;s long-term goals.</p><div class="truth-post-content-high  inline-callout-container" id="truth-255792"><aside class=" callout inline-callout callout--subscribe callout--light" id="truth-255392">
<h4>Never miss another story</h4>
<p>Get the news you want, delivered to your inbox every day.</p>
